Introduction

The purpose of this script is to analyse and check for spatial autocorrelation of the distribution of unmarried men in Denmark. The spatial analysis is performed at a municipality level using Moranâs I test.

Loading in both the map containing municipality multipolygons and civilstatus data for Danish citizens.

Everything appears to look fine. Aarhus Kommune seems to have an extraordinary high percentage of unmarried men. As a large part of the population consists of students, this is in accordance with our expectations. Now we can proceed to perform the statistical correlation analysis using Moranâs I test.

Spatial Autocorrelation analysis

# Simplifying the multipolygon boundaries to minimise compute intensity
mun_simple <- st_cast(st_simplify(mun, dTolerance = 250), to = "MULTIPOLYGON")

# Create neighbour list following queen adjacency
nb <- poly2nb(mun_simple$geometry)

# Get center points of each municipality
mun_centers <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(mun_simple$geometry))

# Plot map with the intermunicipality connections
plot(mun_simple$geometry)
plot(nb, mun_centers, col = "red", add = TRUE)

# Perform analytical Moran I test on percentage of unmarried men in 2020 across
# the 99 Danish municipalities
moran.test(unmarried_men_pr_region$pct_unmarried, nb2listw(nb, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE), 
    zero.policy = TRUE)

    Moran I test under randomisation

data:  unmarried_men_pr_region$pct_unmarried  
weights: nb2listw(nb, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)  n reduced by no-neighbour observations
  

Moran I statistic standard deviate = 0.070267, p-value = 0.472
alternative hypothesis: greater
sample estimates:
Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
     -0.005678456      -0.011111111       0.005977509 
# Perform Moran I test on percentage of unmarried men in 2020 across the 99
# Danish municipalities using MC simulations
moran.mc(unmarried_men_pr_region$pct_unmarried, nb2listw(nb, zero.policy = TRUE), 
    zero.policy = TRUE, nsim = 999)

    Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I

data:  unmarried_men_pr_region$pct_unmarried 
weights: nb2listw(nb, zero.policy = TRUE)  
number of simulations + 1: 1000 

statistic = -0.0056785, observed rank = 523, p-value = 0.477
alternative hypothesis: greater

Conclusion

Both the analytical approach and the simulation based approach for analysing the spatial correlation yielded z-scores (slightly negative ~ -0.006) close to 0 and both scores were not significant (p>0.05). This means that we cannot reject the null hypothesis and, hence, suggests that the distribution of unmarried men in 2020 is not spatially correlated at a municipality level. Thus unmarried men are spatially distributed randomly across Denmark and the are no inter-dependencies across municipality borders.
It would be interesting to run a similar analysis at a more fine-grained level of geographical tessellation (e.g.Â zip codes) or with different definitions of neighbours.
